  "local_port": 34066,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What can I do to get rid of pimples that won't go away?",
  "response": "Dealing with stubborn pimples can be frustrating, but there are several steps you can take to help clear them up. Here\u2019s a comprehensive approach:\n\n### 1. **Cleanse Your Skin Properly**\n   - **Use a gentle cleanser:** Wash your face twice daily with a mild, non-comedogenic cleanser to remove dirt, oil, and makeup without irritating your skin.\n   - **Avoid scrubbing:** Harsh scrubbing can irritate the skin and worsen pimples.\n\n### 2. **Exfoliate Regularly**\n   - **Use a chemical exfoliant:** Products containing salicylic acid (beta hydroxy acid) or glycolic acid (alpha hydroxy acid) can help unclog pores and remove dead skin cells.\n   - **Limit exfoliation:** Over-exfoliating can irritate your skin, so aim for 2-3 times per week.\n\n### 3. **Spot Treatments**\n   - **Benzoyl peroxide:** This helps kill bacteria and reduce inflammation. Start with a lower concentration (2.5% or 5%) to avoid drying out your skin.\n   - **Salicylic acid:** Helps unclog pores and reduce swelling.\n   - **Tea tree oil:** A natural alternative with antibacterial properties. Dilute it with a carrier oil before applying.\n\n### 4. **Moisturize**\n   - **Use a non-comedogenic moisturizer:** Even if you have oily skin, keeping it hydrated is important to maintain your skin\u2019s barrier function.\n\n### 5. **Avoid Touching Your Face**\n   - Touching your face can transfer bacteria and oils, which can worsen pimples.\n\n### 6. **Change Pillowcases and Towels**\n   - Dirty pillowcases and towels can harbor bacteria. Change them regularly, ideally every few days.\n\n### 7. **Be Mindful of Your Diet**\n   - **Limit dairy and sugary foods:** Some studies suggest that these can trigger acne in certain individuals.\n   - **Stay hydrated:** Drinking plenty of water helps maintain skin health.\n\n### 8. **Use Non-Comedogenic Makeup and Skincare Products**\n   - These products are formulated not to clog pores.\n\n### 9. **Consider Over-the-Counter Retinoids**\n   - Retinoids can help increase cell turnover and prevent clogged pores. Start with a low concentration and use at night.\n\n### 10. **Seek Professional Help**\n   - **Dermatologist consultation:** If over-the-counter treatments aren\u2019t working, a dermatologist can prescribe stronger medications like topical or oral antibiotics, retinoids, or hormonal treatments.\n   - **Procedures:** Dermatologists can also perform procedures like chemical peels, laser therapy, or extractions to help clear up stubborn pimples.\n\n### 11. **Be Patient**\n   - It can take several weeks to see noticeable improvements. Consistency is key.\n\nRemember, everyone\u2019s skin is different, so what works for one person might not work for another. If you\u2019re unsure about what to use or if your acne is severe, it\u2019s always best to consult a dermatologist for personalized advice.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
